      "text": "### February 18, 2025\n\n### VIA eTariff Filing\n\nThe Honorable Debbie-Anne A. Reese, Secretary \nFederal Energy Regulatory Commission \n888 First Street, N.E. \nWashington, D.C. 20426 \n\n### Re: RENEW Northeast, Inc. vs ISO New England Inc. and New England Participating Transmission Owners Docket No. EL23-16-___ and ER25-___\n\nDear Secretary Reese: \nThe Participating Transmission Owners Administrative Committee (“PTO AC”), on \nbehalf of the New England Participating Transmission Owners 1 (“PTOs”), and ISO New \nEngland Inc. (“ISO-NE” or the “ISO”) (together, the “Filing Parties”) respectfully jointly submit \nproposed revisions to the ISO-NE Open Access Transmission Tariff (“OATT”) 2 in response to \nthe December 19, 2024 Order on Complaint by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission \n(“Commission”). 3 Specifically, this filing revises Schedules 11, 22, 23, and 25 and \nAttachment F, Appendix C of the OATT, in compliance with the Commission’s directives in \nordering paragraph (C) in the Order on Complaint. 4 The PTO AC and ISO-NE respectfully \nrequest that the proposed OATT revisions take effect on December 19, 2024, the date of the \nOrder on Complaint, and that the Commission act on this filing no later than April 17, 2025 \n1 The PTOs are: Town of Braintree Electric Light Department; Central Maine Power Company; Chicopee \nElectric Light Department; Connecticut Municipal Electric Energy Cooperative; Connecticut Transmission \nMunicipal Electric Energy Cooperative (“CTMEEC”); Eversource Energy Service Company on behalf of The \nConnecticut Light and Power Company, Public Service Company of New Hampshire (“PSNH”) and NSTAR \nElectric Company (“NSTAR”); Fitchburg Gas and Electric Light Company; Green Mountain Power \nCorporation (“GMP”); Town of Hudson Light and Power Department; Maine Electric Power Company \n(“MEPCO”); The City of Holyoke Gas and Electric Department; Massachusetts Municipal Wholesale Electric \nCompany (“MMWEC”); Town of Middleborough Gas & Electric Department; The Narragansett Electric \nCompany d/b/a Rhode Island Energy; New England Power Company d/b/a National Grid; New Hampshire \nElectric Cooperative, Inc.; New Hampshire Transmission, LLC (“NHT”); Town of Norwood Municipal Light \nDepartment; Town of Reading Municipal Light Department; Shrewsbury Electric and Cable Operations; Stowe \nElectric Department; Taunton Municipal Lighting Plant; The United Illuminating Company; Unitil Energy \nSystems, Inc.; Vermont Electric Cooperative, Inc.; Vermont Electric Power Company, Inc.; Vermont Public \nPower Supply Authority; Vermont Transco, LLC; Versant Power (“Versant” or “VP”); and Town of \nWallingford, Connecticut Department of Public Utilities Electric Division. \n2 The OATT is Section II of the ISO New England Inc. Transmission, Markets and Services Tariff (“Tariff”). \n3 RENEW Northeast, Inc., 189 FERC ¶ 61,216 (2024) (“Order on Complaint”). \n4 The Filing Parties note that the rights under Section 205 of the FPA to modify terms, conditions and rates in \nSchedules 22, 23, and 25 of the OATT are shared between the ISO and the PTOs in the manner specified in \nArticle 3.04 of the Transmission Operating Agreement between the PTOs and the ISO (the “TOA”). The ISO \njoins this filing as it relates to those filing rights. The PTOs jointly hold the Schedule 11 and Attachment F, \nAppendix C filing rights. \nSecretary Debbie-Anne A. Reese \nFebruary 18, 2025 \nPage 2 \n(60 days from the date hereof) or earlier, if possible, in order to allow implementation of the \nOrder on Complaint as soon as practicable. \nI. Background \nThe Order on Complaint was issued in response to a complaint filed by RENEW \nNortheast, Inc. on December 13, 2022 (“Complaint”) against ISO-NE and the PTOs. The \nComplaint asserted that certain sections of the OATT are unjust and unreasonable to the extent \nthat they permit PTOs to directly assign to Interconnection Customers 5 the operations and \nmaintenance (“O&M) costs associated with Network Upgrades, Stand-Alone Network Upgrades, \nand Distribution Upgrades (collectively referred to as “Network Upgrades”). 6 The Order on \nComplaint granted the Complaint in part and denied it in part, and the Commission directed a \ncompliance filing within 60 days of the date of the Order on Complaint. \nII. This Filing \nOrdering paragraph (C) of the Order on Complaint directed (1) ISO-NE and the PTOs to \nremove from the OATT any language providing for the assignment of operations and \nmaintenance (“O&M”) costs for Network Upgrades to Interconnection Customers; and (2) the \nPTOs to revise the definition of Interested Party in the Formula Rate Protocols and to delete from \n§ VI.7 of the Formula Rate Protocols the restriction that prevents all Interested Parties from \nattempting to resolve potential disputes. \nTo comply with the first directive in ordering paragraph (C), this filing proposes the \nfollowing changes to the OATT: \nSchedule 11 \n• Section 3.d: This section describes cost responsibility for Category A and Category B Projects, which are Network Upgrades associated with certain generation projects that were under development in the late 1990s. Cost responsibility for these upgrades is split between Regional Network Load and certain Generator Owners. The proposed tariff changes eliminate the Generator Owners’ obligations for O&M and A&G expenses and annual property and payroll taxes associated with Network Upgrades, while retaining Generator Owners’ obligations to pay for costs related to the initial capital costs of any PTO-funded upgrades. \n• Section 5: This section describes cost responsibility for Category C Projects, which encompass all other Network Upgrades and Interconnection Facilities constructed for \n5 Interconnection Customer is defined as “any entity, including a transmission owner or its Affiliates or \nsubsidiaries, that interconnects or proposes to interconnect its Generating Facility with the Administered \nTransmission System.” Tariff, § I.2 (Rules of Construction; Definitions) and OATT, Schedule 22, (Large \nGenerator Interconnection Procedures), § 1. Unless indicated otherwise, all capitalized terms not defined herein \nshall have the same meaning given to them in the Tariff. \n6 Order on Complaint at P 1. \nSecretary Debbie-Anne A. Reese \nFebruary 18, 2025 \nPage 3 \nGenerator Owners that were not classified as Category A or Category B facilities. The \nproposed tariff changes eliminate the Generator Owners’ obligations for O&M and A&G \nexpenses, annual property and payroll taxes and other related costs associated with Network \nUpgrades, while retaining Generator Owners’ obligations to pay for costs related to the initial \ncapital costs of any PTO-funded upgrades. \n• Section 7: This section addresses contract and credit requirements. The proposed tariff changes: (a) clarify that certain language applies only to construction-related costs, and (b) confirm that cost exclusions required by the Order on Complaint continue to apply in the event that a Generator Owner goes out of business. \n• Section 8: This new section states that effective December 19, 2024, Interconnection Customers will no longer be responsible for the costs associated with Network Upgrades that the Commission directed be removed, and thus, any payments made by Interconnection Customers for such costs that accrued after December 19, 2024 will be refunded, along with interest. This new section will allow the PTOs to issue refunds to Generator Owners upon the Commission’s acceptance of the tariff changes proposed in this compliance filing, without requiring modifications to individual Interconnection Agreements that include the assignment of such costs. Schedule 22 \n• Appendix 6, Article 10.2: This section of the pro forma Large Generator Interconnection Agreement addresses O&M costs, including potential repairs and replacements, associated with Network Upgrades. The proposed edits are intended to clarify that neither O&M expenses nor capital costs related to repairs and replacements of N",
